    <svcsubproc>
        <title>Windshield Washer Fluid Reservoir</title>
        <para>The windshield washer fluid reservoir assembly is comprised of five main components: reservoir mounting
            bracket, reservoir, fluid pump, harness and supply hose to the windshield wiper assemblies. To replace the
            reservoir:
        </para>
        <figure id="f47006145" figsize="pg-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figg47/G47006145.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="288px"
                     scalefitheight="288px"/>
            <caption>Figure 145. Windshield Washer Fluid Reservoir</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1>1. RESERVOIR REFILL CAP</callout1>
                <callout1>2. FLUID RESERVOIR</callout1>
                <callout1>3. RESERVOIR SUPPLY PUMP</callout1>
                <callout1>4. WINDSHIELD WASHER HOSE SUPPLY LINE</callout1>
                <callout1>5. RESERVOIR BOTTLE MOUNTING BOLTS</callout1>
                <callout1>6. RESERVOIR MOUNTING BRACKET</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Open hood and locate windshield washer fluid reservoir on forward passenger side of frame
                rail.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">To remove reservoir, locate and disconnect windshield washer fluid supply pump harness (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f47006146">Figure 146, Item 2</hotlnk>.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f47005146" figsize="pg-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figg47/G47006146.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="288px"
                     scalefitheight="288px"/>
            <caption>Figure 146. Reservoir Pump Removal</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1>1. WASHER FLUID RESERVOIR</callout1>
                <callout1>2. PUMP HARNESS CONNECTION</callout1>
                <callout1>3. FRONT END PIG TAIL HARNESS</callout1>
                <callout1>4. RESERVOIR SUPPLY NIPPLE CONNECTION</callout1>
                <callout1>5. RESERVOIR SUPPLY PUMP</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <figure id="f47006147" figsize="pg-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figg47/G47006147.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="288px"
                     scalefitheight="288px"/>
            <caption>Figure 147. Pump Connection Disconnect</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1>1. FLUID RESERVOIR</callout1>
                <callout1>2. PUMP HARNESS CONNECTION</callout1>
                <callout1>3. FRONT END HARNESS CONNECTIONS</callout1>
                <callout1>4. WINDSHIELD WASHER FLUID SUPPLY HOSE CONNECTION</callout1>
                <callout1>5. WINDSHIELD WASHER FLUID PUMP</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">With reservoir pump connection harness unplugged (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f47006147">Figure 147, Item 2</hotlnk>), locate and disconnect windshield wiper washer
                supply hose from pump nipple (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f47006148">Figure 148, Item 3</hotlnk>).
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Let fluid in reservoir drain. Use clean container to save the washer fluid.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">When fluid is drained from reservoir, remove pump assembly.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">When removing pump assembly, lift and pull pump housing.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Pump will pop out when pulled out and way from reservoir.</para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f47006148" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figg47/G47006148.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="272px"
                     scalefitheight="248px"/>
            <caption>Figure 148. Supply Hose To Wiper Disconnect</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1>1. WASHER FLUID RESERVOIR</callout1>
                <callout1>2. WASHER FLUID SUPPLY HOSE</callout1>
                <callout1>3. WASHER FLUID PUMP OUTLET</callout1>
                <callout1>4. WASHER FLUID PUMP</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <figure id="f47006149" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figg47/G47006149.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="272px"
                     scalefitheight="256px"/>
            <caption>Figure 149. Reservoir Pump Removal</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1>1. RESERVOIR PUMP MOUNTING HOLE</callout1>
                <callout1>2. PUMP NIPPLE</callout1>
                <callout1>3. WINDSHIELD WASHER SUPPLY PUMP</callout1>
                <callout1>4. HARNESS FRONT END PIG TAIL CONNECTION</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <figure id="f47006150" figsize="pg-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figg47/G47006150.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="288px"
                     scalefitheight="288px"/>
            <caption>Figure 150. Pump Reservoir Tank Seal</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1>1. PUMP / RESERVOIR SEAL</callout1>
                <callout1>2. RESERVOIR PUMP</callout1>
                <callout1>3. RESERVOIR NIPPLE</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">With pump out of reservoir, check seal at bottom of pump nipple.</para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f47006151" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figg47/G47006151.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="272px"
                     scalefitheight="272px"/>
            <caption>Figure 151. Reservoir Removal</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1>1. FLUID RESERVOIR</callout1>
                <callout1>2. RESERVOIR MOUNTING BOLTS</callout1>
                <callout1>3. RESERVOIR MOUNTING BRACKETS</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
